<br>
Religion is merely a tool to instruct/enforce morality.<br>
<br>
But that being said, I fall somewhere in the native belief scheme, although I am hesitant to call it religion. When I was young, I was a hardcore bible thumper on the protestant christian side of things (compounded with being sent to a catholic school). Going to college, I was exposed to so many more religious views than I had ever seen during my sheltered christian life. During that time, I became fascinated with and started to explore my native cultural past. Once I was exposed to that, I started to realize that christianity was something that was too harsh on the world... too filled with hate and unbendable ways.<br>
<br>
In something that you think only happens in books or movies, a kind native shaman took me under his wing for a few years. It was an increadible spiritual awakening that helped me to see and interact with the world in a different light.<br>
<br>
Since then, learning about different religions/cults has become a bit of a passtime. Once you become tolerant of other's beliefs, it is easier to interact with them.<br>
<br>
Well, except for a number of death/harbinger religions. Those are the groups that the world can do without. Folks use Cthulhu as the basis of jokes, but you would be surprised at the large number of people dedicated to it. <p><TABLE ALIGN="center"><TR><TD>
